.PP
For the single-line summary use
.BR stryke (1)
or
.BR s (1).
.SH NAME
stryke, s \- highly parallel Perl 5 interpreter with shell-grade REPL
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B s
[\fIOPTION\fR]... [\fB--\fR] [\fIPROGRAMFILE\fR] [\fIARGUMENT\fR]...
.br
.B s \fICODE\fR
.RB " (" -e " optional when arg looks like code)"
.br
.B s \fIBUILTIN\fR [\fIARGS\fR]
.RB " (" -e " not needed; calls builtin directly)"
.br
.B s \fISUBCOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B stryke
is a single-binary Perl 5 interpreter written in Rust with parallel
extensions, a Cranelift JIT, pipe-forward (\fB|>\fR), the thread macro
(\fB~>\fR), 10,459 primary builtins in
.BR %b ,
and an interactive REPL that doubles as a Unix shell.
.PP
The interpreter compiles source to a 346-opcode bytecode running on a
register+stack hybrid VM; hot blocks are JIT'd to native code via
Cranelift. Parallel primitives (\fBpmap\fR / \fBpgrep\fR / \fBpfor\fR /
\fBpsort\fR / \fBpreduce\fR) ride on rayon work-stealing across every
available core.
.PP
The binary is invoked as
.B s
by default;
.B stryke
and
.B st
are alternate spellings, all routing to the same entry point.
.PP
.B stryke
is also a coreutils-style command launcher: when called with one
argument matching a known builtin name plus its arguments, stryke
invokes that builtin directly. Example:
.RS 4
.EX
s basename /a/b/c.txt    # prints: c.txt
s sha256 myfile          # prints SHA-256 digest
s len 'hello'            # prints: 5
.EE
.RE
.SH "1.  INVOCATION"
.SS "1.1  Execution"
.TP
\fB'\fR\fICODE\fR\fB'\fR
Inline code; \fB-e\fR is optional when the argument looks like code.
.TP
.B -e \fICODE\fR
Explicit inline; required with \fB-n\fR, \fB-p\fR, \fB-l\fR, \fB-a\fR.
.TP
.B -E \fICODE\fR
Like \fB-e\fR but enables all optional features (Perl 5
.BR feature .pm-style
preloads).
.TP
.IB BUILTIN " [" ARGS "]"
Direct builtin invocation (no \fB-e\fR needed).
.TP
.B --script
Force script lookup when a name conflicts with a builtin
(\fBs --script basename\fR runs \fI./basename\fR).
.TP
.B -c
Check syntax only; parse without compile/run.
.TP
.BR --lint ", " --check
Parse + compile to bytecode without running.
.TP
.BR --disasm ", " --disassemble
Print bytecode disassembly to stderr before VM run.
.TP
.B --ast
Dump parsed AST as JSON and exit (no execution).
.TP
.B --fmt
Pretty-print parsed Perl to stdout and exit.
.TP
.B --explain \fICODE\fR
Print expanded hint for an error code (e.g. \fBE0001\fR) and exit.
.TP
.B --profile
Wall-clock profile to stderr (VM op lines; flamegraph-ready).
.TP
.B --flame
Flamegraph: terminal bars (TTY) or SVG (piped to file).
.TP
.B --no-jit
Disable Cranelift JIT (bytecode interpreter only).
.TP
.B --compat
Perl 5 strict-compat: disable all stryke extensions.
.TP
.B --no-interop
Reject Perl-isms; force idiomatic stryke
(\fB$_0\fR/\fB$_1\fR over \fB$a\fR/\fB$b\fR; \fBfn\fR not \fBsub\fR).
.TP
.B -d\fR[\fBt\fR][\fI:MOD\fR]
Run program under debugger or module \fIDevel::MOD\fR.
.TP
.B -D\fR[\fInumber/letters\fR]
Set debugging flags.
.TP
.B -u
Dump core after parsing program.
.TP
.B --record
Record every run to \fI~/.stryke/perf.sqlite\fR for inspection via
\fBperfview\fR.
.SS "1.2  Input Processing"
.TP
.B -n
Assume \fBwhile (<>) { ... }\fR loop around program.
.TP
.B -p
Like \fB-n\fR but print each \fB$_\fR after the loop body (sed-style).
.TP
.B -a
Autosplit mode (splits \fB$_\fR into \fB@F\fR).
.TP
.B -F\fI/pattern/\fR
\fBsplit()\fR pattern for \fB-a\fR.
.TP
.B -l\fR[\fIoctnum\fR]
Enable line ending processing.
.TP
.B -0\fR[\fIoctal\fR]
Specify record separator (\fB\\0\fR if no arg).
.TP
.B -g
Slurp all input at once (alias for \fB-0777\fR).
.TP
.B -i\fR[\fIextension\fR]
Edit \fB<>\fR files in place; multiple files processed in parallel.
.SS "1.3  Modules & Paths"
.TP
.B -M \fIMODULE\fR
Execute \fBuse \fIMODULE\fR before program.
.TP
.B -m \fIMODULE\fR
Execute \fBuse \fIMODULE\fB ()\fR before program (no import).
.TP
.B -I \fIDIRECTORY\fR
Specify \fB@INC\fR directory (multiple allowed).
.TP
.B -f
Don't do \fI$sitelib/sitecustomize.pl\fR at startup.
.TP
.B -S
Look for programfile using \fB$PATH\fR.
.TP
.B -x\fR[\fIdirectory\fR]
Ignore text before \fB#!perl\fR line.
.SS "1.4  Unicode & Safety"
.TP
.B -C\fR[\fInumber/list\fR]
Enable listed Unicode features.
.TP
.B -t
Tainting warnings.
.TP
.B -T
Tainting checks.
.TP
.B -U
Allow unsafe operations.
.TP
.B -s
Switch parsing for programfile args.
.SS "1.5  Warnings"
.TP
.B -w
Many useful warnings.
.TP
.B -W
All warnings.
.TP
.B -X
No warnings.
.SS "1.6  Info"
.TP
.B -v
Version, patchlevel, license.
.TP
.B -V\fR[\fB:\fIconfigvar\fR]
Configuration summary.
.TP
.BR -h ", " --help
Help.
.SS "1.7  Parallelism"
.TP
.B -j \fIN\fR
Set rayon pool size to \fIN\fR threads.
.SS "1.8  Subcommands"
.TP
.B docs \fR[\fITOPIC\fR]
TUI hover-doc reader (vi-style nav: j/k/d/u/]/[ /t / / : r ? q).
Aliases:
.BR help ", " h .
.TP
.B repl \fR[\fB--load \fIFILE\fR]
Interactive REPL with optional pre-load.
.TP
.B serve \fR[\fIPORT\fR] [\fISCRIPT\fR]
HTTP server.
.TP
.B fmt \fR[\fB-i\fR] \fIFILE\fR...
Format source files.
.TP
.B bench \fR[\fIFILE|DIR\fR]
Run benchmarks.
.TP
.B init \fR[\fINAME\fR]
Scaffold project in cwd.
.TP
.B new \fINAME\fR
Scaffold project at \fI./NAME/\fR.
.TP
.B install \fR[\fB--offline\fR]
Resolve deps, populate \fIstryke.lock\fR + \fI~/.stryke/store\fR.
.TP
.B add \fINAME\fR[\fB@\fIVER\fR] ...
Add dep to \fIstryke.toml\fR. Flags:
.B --dev \fR/\fR --group=\fIN\fR \fR/\fR --path=\fIDIR\fR \fR/\fR --features=\fIA,B\fR.
.TP
.B remove \fINAME\fR
Drop dep from \fIstryke.toml\fR.
.TP
.B tree
Print resolved dep graph from \fIstryke.lock\fR.
.TP
.B info \fINAME\fR
Show lockfile entry + store path.
.TP
.B pkg \fISUBCOMMAND\fR
Dispatcher for package commands.
.TP
.B build \fISCRIPT\fR \fR[\fB-o \fIOUT\fR]
AOT bundle SCRIPT into a copy of this binary as a standalone exe.
.TP
.B --lsp
Language Server (JSON-RPC on stdio); must be sole arg.
.TP
.B --remote-worker
Persistent cluster worker (stdio); sole arg.
.TP
.B --remote-worker-v1
Legacy one-shot worker (stdio); sole arg.
.TP
.B t \fR[\fIFILE|DIR\fR]
Run tests from \fIt/\fR (test files matching \fItest_*.stk\fR).
Parallel by default; flags \fB--quiet\fR, \fB--summary\fR.
.TP
.B perfview \fR[options]
Read the wall-clock perf log from \fI~/.stryke/perf.sqlite\fR.
Options: \fBtop \fIN\fR, \fBname \fISUB\fR, \fBre \fIREGEX\fR,
\fBpath \fI/abs\fR, \fBsince \fI7d\fR, \fBslowest / fastest / recent\fR.
.SH "2.  LEXICAL STRUCTURE"
.SS "2.1  Comments"
.PP
Line comments start with
.BR # ;
they extend to end of line. No block-comment syntax.
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
# This is a comment
my $x = 1   # trailing
.EE
.RE
.SS "2.2  Identifiers"
.PP
Identifiers match
.B [A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*
plus Unicode XID. Package separators:
.B ::
.RB "(e.g. " "Foo::Bar::baz" ).
Sigils:
.BR $  ", " @  ", " %  ", " &  ", " *
for scalars, arrays, hashes, code, and typeglobs.
.SS "2.3  Strings"
.PP
.TP
.B '...'
Single quotes; no interpolation, no escapes except
.B \\'
and
.BR \\\\ .
.TP
.B "..."
Double quotes; full interpolation:
.BR $var ", " @arr ", " "${complex}" ", " "${$ref}" ", " "@{[expr]}" ", " "${\\expr}" .
Escapes:
.BR \\n " \\t \\r \\0 \\xNN \\uNNNN \\\\ \\\""
+ \\e \\a \\f \\b \\v.
.TP
.B q(...)
Like single quotes, with custom delimiter (any matched bracket pair
or non-alphanumeric char).
.TP
.B qq(...)
Like double quotes, with custom delimiter.
.TP
.B qw(LIST)
Word list, whitespace-separated.
.TP
.B qr/PATTERN/
Compiled regex literal.
.TP
.BI <<EOT ... EOT
Heredoc (newline-terminated;
.B <<~EOT
strips leading indentation).
.SS "2.4  Numbers"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
123       # decimal
0x1A      # hex
0b1010    # binary
0o17      # octal (stryke-style)
0755      # octal (Perl-style)
3.14      # float
1.5e-3    # scientific
1_000_000 # underscore-separated
.EE
.RE
.SS "2.5  Regex Literals"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
m/PATTERN/FLAGS   # match (m// is optional with / delimiters)
s/PATTERN/REPL/FLAGS  # substitute
tr/SRC/DST/FLAGS  # transliterate
qr/PATTERN/FLAGS  # compiled regex value
.EE
.RE
Flags:
.B i
(case-insensitive),
.B m
(multiline),
.B s
(dotall),
.B x
(extended),
.B g
(global),
.B e
(eval RHS),
.B r
(return; don't mutate).
.SH "3.  DATA TYPES"
.SS "3.1  Scalars"
.B StrykeValue
is NaN-boxed: immediates (
.BR undef ", "
i32, f64) and Arc-tagged heap objects (BigInt, String, Bytes, Array,
Hash, ArrayRef, HashRef, ScalarRef, CodeRef, Regex, Blessed, IOHandle,
Set, Deque, Heap, sketches: BloomFilter, HllSketch, CmsSketch,
TopKSketch, TDigestSketch, RoaringBitmap, RateLimiter, HashRing,
SimHash, MinHash, IntervalTree, BkTree, Rope).
.SS "3.2  Arrays"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my @arr = (1, 2, 3);
$arr[0]        # element
@arr[1..2]     # slice
@arr[1:2]      # slice with stryke colon range (1:N inclusive)
scalar @arr    # length (Perl convention)
len(@arr)      # length (stryke convention)
push @arr, 4
pop @arr
unshift @arr, 0
shift @arr
.EE
.RE
.SS "3.3  Hashes"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my %h = (a => 1, b => 2);
$h{a}          # element
@h{qw(a b)}    # slice
keys %h
values %h
exists $h{a}
delete $h{a}
%h = ()        # clear
.EE
.RE
.SS "3.4  References"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $ref = \@arr;       # scalar ref to array
$$ref                  # deref scalar
@$ref                  # deref array
@{$ref}                # explicit
$ref->[0]              # arrow deref array element
$ref->{key}            # arrow deref hash element
&$cref()               # call coderef
$cref->(args)          # call coderef (preferred)
ref($x)                # "ARRAY" / "HASH" / "CODE" / etc.
.EE
.RE
.SS "3.5  Classes (stryke extension)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
class Point {
    x: Num = 0
    y: Num = 0
    fn distance($other) {
        sqrt(($self->x - $other->x)**2 + ($self->y - $other->y)**2)
    }
    fn Self.origin() { Point() }
}
my $p = Point(x => 3, y => 4)
p $p->distance(Point::origin())   # 5
.EE
.RE
.SS "3.6  Structs (stryke extension)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
struct Foo { a: Int, b: Str }
my $f = Foo(a => 1, b => "hi")
.EE
.RE
.SS "3.7  Enums (stryke extension)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
enum Shape {
    Circle(r: Num),
    Square(side: Num),
    Triangle(a: Num, b: Num, c: Num),
}
my $s = Circle(r => 5)
match ($s) {
    Circle($r)    => p "circle r=$r",
    Square($side) => p "square side=$side",
    _             => p "other",
}
.EE
.RE
.SS "3.8  Sets / Deques / Heaps / Sketches"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $s = set(1, 2, 3, 2, 1)             # uniq
$s->contains(2)                        # 1
$s->union(set(4, 5))

my $dq = deque(1, 2, 3)
$dq->push_front(0); $dq->pop_back

my $h = heap(5, 3, 8, 1)               # min-heap
$h->pop                                # 1
$h->peek                               # 3

my $b = bloom_filter(10_000, 0.001)    # capacity, fpr
bloom_add($b, "alice")
bloom_contains($b, "alice")            # 1

my $hll = hll(14)                      # precision 14 → 16k registers
hll_add($hll, $_) for 1..100_000
hll_count($hll)                        # ~99672, ~0.33% error

my $td = t_digest(100)
td_add($td, $_) for @samples
td_quantile($td, 0.99)                 # 99th percentile

my $rb = roaring(1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13)
rb_and($rb, roaring(2, 4, 6, 8))       # in-place intersect
rb_to_array($rb)                       # (2, 8)
.EE
.RE
.SH "4.  OPERATORS"
.SS "4.1  Arithmetic"
.B + - * / % ** //
(integer division)
.B ++ --
.SS "4.2  Comparison (numeric)"
.B == != < > <= >= <=>
(spaceship)
.SS "4.3  Comparison (string)"
.B eq ne lt gt le ge cmp
.SS "4.4  Logical"
.B && || ! //
.RB "(defined-or), word forms: " "and or not xor" .
.SS "4.5  Bitwise"
.B & | ^ ~ << >>
.SS "4.6  String"
.B .
.RB "(concat), " x " (repeat)."
.SS "4.7  Range"
.B 1..N
(inclusive Perl range),
.B 1:N
(stryke colon range \(em inclusive, supports floats and reverse).
.SS "4.8  Regex"
.B =~ !~
match/no-match.
.SS "4.9  Ternary"
.B COND ? T : F
.SS "4.10  Pipe-Forward (stryke extension)"
.B EXPR |> FN
.RB "passes the LHS as the first argument to " FN .
Compose stages left-to-right:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
@nums |> grep { _ > 0 } |> map { _ * 2 } |> sum
.EE
.RE
.SS "4.11  Thread Macro (stryke extension)"
.B ~> EXPR FN FN ...
threads
.B EXPR
through each
.B FN
sequentially:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
~> "Hello, World!"
    .uc
    .reverse
    .substr(0, 5)
.EE
.RE
.PP
.B ~>>
is the parallel variant (each stage runs in its own task).
.SS "4.12  Topic Slots"
.PP
.TP
.B $_
Perl-compat topic.
.TP
.B _
Stryke topic (same value, unsigiled, only inside blocks/closures).
.TP
.B _0 _1 _2 ...
Positional block parameters (0-indexed). Replaces the
.BR $a "/" $b
magic in sort/reduce.
.TP
.B $_<
.RB "Outer topic in a nested " ~> " chain."
.TP
.B $_<<
.RB "Outer-outer (each " < " climbs one chain level)."
.SS "4.13  Sketch Algebra (stryke extension)"
.PP
Probabilistic data structures are first-class operands for
.BR + " | & ^ - " .
No other language ships this as a syntactic primitive \(em
everywhere else these are library function calls
.RB ( bloom_union(a, b) ", " hll.merge(other) ", " roaring.intersect ).
Operators are functional: a fresh sketch is returned, neither
operand is mutated.
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $u = $bloom_a + $bloom_b;       # Bloom union (also: |)
my $u = $hll_a   + $hll_b;         # HyperLogLog union (also: |)
my $u = $cms_a   + $cms_b;         # Count-Min counter sum
my $u = $topk_a  + $topk_b;        # SpaceSaving heavy-hitter merge
my $u = $td_a    + $td_b;          # t-digest centroid merge
my $u = $rb_a | $rb_b;             # Roaring union
my $i = $rb_a & $rb_b;             # Roaring intersection
my $x = $rb_a ^ $rb_b;             # Roaring symmetric difference
my $d = $rb_a - $rb_b;             # Roaring andnot (set difference)
.EE
.RE
.PP
Mismatched shapes (e.g. HLL precision mismatch, Bloom capacity
mismatch) fall back to the default numeric/bitwise operator path
\(em no panic, no truncation.
.SH "5.  CONTROL FLOW"
.SS "5.1  Conditionals"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
if (COND)    { ... } elsif (COND) { ... } else { ... }
unless (COND) { ... }                  # equivalent to if (!COND)
EXPR if COND                           # postfix
EXPR unless COND                       # postfix
.EE
.RE
.SS "5.2  Loops"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
while (COND) { ... }
until (COND) { ... }
do { ... } while (COND)
for (INIT; COND; STEP) { ... }
for/foreach my $v (@list) { ... }
EXPR while COND                        # postfix
EXPR for @list                         # postfix
.EE
.RE
.SS "5.3  Loop Control"
.B last
.RB "(break), " next " (continue), " redo " (re-enter without re-test)."
Block labels:
.B LABEL: while ... { last LABEL; }
.SS "5.4  Algebraic Match (stryke extension)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
match ($val) {
    /^\\d+$/         => p "number: $val",
    [1, 2, _]        => p "array starting 1,2",
    { name => $n }   => p "name is $n",
    Point($x, $y)    => p "point $x,$y",
    _                => p "default",
}
.EE
.RE
.SS "5.5  Try/Catch (stryke extension)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
try {
    risky_op();
} catch ($err) {
    p "caught: $err"
} finally {
    cleanup()
}
.EE
.RE
.PP
Equivalent Perl 5 form: \fBeval { ... }; if ($@) { ... }\fR.
.SH "6.  SUBROUTINES"
.SS "6.1  sub (Perl-compat)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
sub greet { my ($name) = @_; "Hello, $name!" }
sub add($a, $b) { $a + $b }            # signatures (Perl 5.20+)
sub circle_area :prototype($) { my $r = shift; PI * $r ** 2 }
.EE
.RE
.SS "6.2  fn (stryke-idiomatic)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
fn add($a, $b) { $a + $b }
fn add($a: Int, $b: Int) { $a + $b }        # typed signature
fn add($a: Int = 0, $b: Int = 0) { ... }    # defaults
fn Foo::add($a, $b) { ... }                  # qualified
fn Foo.bar { ... }                           # method on package
.EE
.RE
.SS "6.3  Anonymous & Closures"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $sq = sub { $_[0] ** 2 };
my $sq = fn { _ ** 2 };                  # stryke: _ is topic
my $f = fn ($x) { $x + 1 };
.EE
.RE
.SS "6.4  Async / Await"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $task = async { expensive_work() };
my $result = await $task;
my @results = await spawn { fetch_url $_ }, @urls;
.EE
.RE
.SS "6.5  Prototypes"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
sub myfn :prototype($\\@$) { ... }       # scalar, array-ref, scalar
.EE
.RE
.SH "7.  SCOPES & PACKAGES"
.SS "7.1  my / our / local / oursync"
.TP
.B my $x
Lexical scope (block-local).
.TP
.B our $x
Package global with lexical alias.
.TP
.B local $x
Dynamic scope (preserved and restored).
.TP
.B oursync $x
Stryke extension: package global with cross-thread synchronized access
(reads acquire shared lock, writes acquire exclusive lock).
.TP
.B mysync $x
Stryke extension: lexical sync — \fBmy\fR scope with cross-thread visibility.
.SS "7.2  package"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
package Foo::Bar;
sub new { bless {}, shift }
1;
.EE
.RE
.SS "7.3  use / require / no"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
use strict;
use warnings;
use feature qw(say signatures);
use Foo::Bar;
use Foo::Bar qw(fn1 fn2);
require "module.pl";
no warnings 'uninitialized';
.EE
.RE
.SS "7.4  Special Blocks"
.B BEGIN { ... }
runs at compile time.
.B END { ... }
runs at exit.
.B INIT { ... }
runs once at start.
.B CHECK { ... }
runs after compile, before run.
.B UNITCHECK { ... }
per-compilation-unit equivalent.
.SH "8.  REGEX"
.PP
Three-tier engine (
.IR regex (1)
crate \(-> fancy-regex \(-> pcre2):
.IP \(bu 2
.B regex
crate handles standard regex with linear-time guarantees.
.IP \(bu 2
.B fancy-regex
adds backrefs, lookarounds, atomic groups.
.IP \(bu 2
.B pcre2
provides PCRE-only verbs (\\K, \\g'name', recursion, named subroutines).
.PP
Stryke picks the lowest tier that handles the pattern.
.SS "8.1  Match"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
"hello" =~ /^h/         # 1
"hello" =~ /(.)(.)/     # captures: $1='h', $2='e'
"abc" =~ /(?<first>.)/  # named: $+{first}='a'
.EE
.RE
.SS "8.2  Substitution"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
$_ = "foo bar";
s/foo/FOO/;             # mutates
my $new = $_ =~ s/o/0/gr;  # non-destructive (r flag)
.EE
.RE
.SS "8.3  Transliteration"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $s = "Hello";
$s =~ tr/a-z/A-Z/;      # HELLO
my $n = $s =~ tr/L//;   # count L's (returns count)
.EE
.RE
.SS "8.4  Compiled Regex Objects"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $re = qr/^\\d+$/;
"123" =~ $re            # 1
.EE
.RE
.SH "9.  OOP (Modern stryke `class` syntax)"
.PP
Stryke supports two OOP styles: Perl 5
.B bless
and the modern
.B class
keyword (cleaner, typed, with traits).
.SS "9.1  Class declaration"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
class Animal {
    name: Str
    age: Int = 0
    fn speak { p "Animal $self->name speaks" }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    breed: Str = "mixed"
    fn speak { p "Woof! I am $self->name" }   # override
    fn bark  { $self->speak() }
}

trait Printable { fn to_str }
class Item impl Printable {
    name: Str
    fn to_str { $self->name }
}

class C extends A, B { }                  # multiple inheritance, C3 MRO
.EE
.RE
.SS "9.2  Construction"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $dog = Dog(name => "Rex", age => 5, breed => "Lab")
my $dog = Dog("Rex", 5, "Lab")              # positional
.EE
.RE
.SS "9.3  Field access (getter / setter)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
p $dog->name        # getter (no args)
$dog->age(6)        # setter (one arg)
.EE
.RE
.SS "9.4  Static methods (fn Self.name)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
class Math {
    fn Self.add($x, $y) { $x + $y }
    fn Self.pi { 3.14159 }
}
p Math::add(3, 4)   # 7
p Math::pi()        # 3.14159
.EE
.RE
.SS "9.5  Introspection"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
$dog->isa("Dog")          # 1
$dog->isa("Animal")       # 1
$dog->fields()            # (name, age, breed)
$dog->to_hash()           # { name=>"Rex", age=>5, breed=>"Lab" }
$dog->with(age => 6)      # functional update (returns new instance)
$dog->clone()             # deep copy
.EE
.RE
.SS "9.6  Visibility"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
class Secret {
    pub  visible: Int = 1
    priv hidden:  Int = 42
    pub fn get_hidden { $self->hidden }
}
.EE
.RE
.SH "10. AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming)"
.PP
Stryke extends Perl 5 with first-class advice on user subs and methods.
.SS "10.1  Intercept"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
intercept Foo::greet  before { p "calling $_->name" }
intercept Foo::greet  after  { p "called  $_->name" }
intercept Foo::greet  around { p "before"; my $r = proceed(); p "after"; $r }
intercept_list                       # list all intercepts
intercept_remove "Foo::greet"        # drop intercepts on greet
intercept_clear                      # drop all
.EE
.RE
.PP
Advice has access to
.B $_->name
(sub name),
.B $_->args
(call args),
.B proceed()
(call the next layer / original),
.B $_->return_value
(in
.BR after ).
.SH "11. PARALLEL PRIMITIVES"
.PP
Rayon-backed work-stealing across all cores. Two syntactic forms per
primitive: block form and bare-fn form.
.SS "11.1  pmap"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my @out = pmap { _ * 2 } 1..1_000_000
my @hashes = pmap sha256 @blobs, progress => 1

# bare-fn form
my @doubled = pmap dbl, 1..100
fn dbl = _ * 2
.EE
.RE
.SS "11.2  pgrep / pfor / psort / preduce / pmap_reduce"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my @errs = pgrep { /ERROR/ } @log_lines
pfor { print_log _ } @files
my @sorted = psort { length _0 <=> length _1 } @strings
my $sum = preduce { _0 + _1 } 1..1000
my $sum = preduce_init 0, { _0 + _1 } @nums
my $total = pmap_reduce { _ * 2 } { _0 + _1 } @nums
.EE
.RE
.SS "11.3  pcache (parallel memoize)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my @results = pcache { expensive(_) } @inputs
.EE
.RE
.SS "11.4  fan / fan_cap"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
fan { hit_endpoint(_) }              # _ is index 0..rayon_pool_size-1
fan_cap 100, { compute_one(_) }      # caps at 100, collects results
.EE
.RE
.SS "11.5  par_walk / par_lines / par_sed"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
par_walk "/tmp", { lstat(_)->[7] > 1_000_000 and p _ }
par_lines "huge.log", { /ERROR/ and p _ }
par_sed qr/foo/, "bar", "*.txt"      # in-place across all files
.EE
.RE
.SS "11.6  ppool / pchannel"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $pool = ppool(4)                  # 4 workers
$pool->submit({ ... }) for @jobs
my @results = $pool->collect()

my ($tx, $rx) = pchannel(64)         # bounded channel
$tx->send($v); my $v = $rx->recv()
.EE
.RE
.SS "11.7  async / spawn / await"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $t = async { expensive_compute() }
my $r = await $t

my @tasks = map { spawn { fetch_url _ } } @urls
my @bodies = await @tasks
.EE
.RE
.SH "12. PIPELINES"
.SS "12.1  Pipe-Forward (|>)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
@nums
  |> grep { _ > 0 }
  |> map  { _ * 2 }
  |> sort { _0 <=> _1 }
  |> head 10
  |> sum
.EE
.RE
.SS "12.2  pipeline() — lazy iterator object"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my @out = pipeline(1:1_000_000)
  ->filter { _ % 3 == 0 }
  ->map    { _ ** 2 }
  ->take(5)
  ->collect
# Stages run on demand; no intermediate arrays allocated.
.EE
.RE
.SS "12.3  par_pipeline / par_pipeline_stream"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
par_pipeline(@in)
  ->map { transform _ }
  ->filter { valid _ }
  ->collect

# Streaming with bounded channels between stages:
par_pipeline_stream(
    source  => fn { while (my $l = <STDIN>) { yield $l } },
    stages  => [
        { name => "parse", map => fn { json_decode } },
        { name => "score", map => fn { compute_score } },
    ],
    workers => 4,
)
.EE
.RE
.SH "13. THREAD MACRO (~> / ~>>)"
.PP
Threads a value through a chain of stages, each of which sees the
running value as
.BR _ .
Distinguishes itself from
.B |>
by allowing each stage to be a complex form, not just a callable.
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
~> "hello world"
    chars             # "h", "e", "l", "l", "o", " ", "w", ...
    grep { _ ne " " }
    uniq
    sort
    join ""           # "delhorw"

# Parallel threading:
~>> 1..1_000_000
    map { sha256 _ }
    grep { /^00/ }
    head 10
.EE
.RE
.PP
.B Outer topic chain:
inside a nested
.BR ~> ,
.B _<
refers to the outer chain's running value;
.B _<<
to the chain one level further out, etc. Each
.B <
climbs one nesting level.
.SH "14. REFLECTION HASHES"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
keys %b           # 10,459 primary builtin names → category
keys %a           # 641 aliases (name → primary)
keys %all         # 11,022 = %b ∪ %a ∪ %k
keys %k           # 85 keywords (if, sub, my, our, …)
keys %pc          # 185 Perl 5 core names (subset of %b)
keys %e           # 10,082 stryke extensions (subset of %b)
keys %d           # 4,228 names with LSP hover documentation
keys %c           # 306 categories
keys %p           # 8,790 primaries (after alias dedup)
keys %o           # 70 operators
keys %v           # 97 special variables ($_, $!, $/, ...)
%parameters       # live binding view of every named pad slot

# Per-package stashes:
keys %main::      # everything in package main
keys %Foo::       # everything in package Foo
.EE
.RE
