.SH "16. REPL & SHELL-LIKE BEHAVIOR"
.PP
Type
.B s
with no arguments to enter the REPL:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
$ s
 ███████╗████████╗██████╗ ██╗   ██╗██╗  ██╗███████╗
 ██╔════╝╚══██╔══╝██╔══██╗╚██╗ ██╔╝██║ ██╔╝██╔════╝
 (banner with reflection counts)

stryke❯ ls
stryke❯ pwd
stryke❯ pushd /tmp
stryke❯ curl_get("https://api.example.com") |> from_json |> to_table |> p
stryke❯ help pmap         # opens TUI hover-doc reader
stryke❯ man ls            # spawns system man(1)
stryke❯ exit              # Ctrl-D also works
.EE
.RE
.PP
Tab completion is backed by
.IR strykelang/lsp_completion_words.txt
(22,071 names: every primary, alias, keyword, special variable, file
test op, glob qualifier). History is reedline-backed and persists
across sessions.
.PP
.B Pipelines in stryke REPL are in-process.
Each
.B |>
stage is a heap-resident
.B StrykeValue
passed to the next stage's function. No fork, no exec, no syscall
boundary. The REPL is the only programming-language prompt that
provides shell-grade UX
.B and
in-process structured pipelines simultaneously.
.SS "16.1  REPL Aliases"
.PP
Bare
.B alias
is reserved for Perl typeglob assignment
.RB ( "*alias = \\&original" ).
REPL alias table lives under
.B repl_alias / repl_unalias / set_alias / unset_alias :
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
stryke❯ repl_alias("ll", "ls -la")
stryke❯ repl_alias("g=git")           # equals-form
stryke❯ repl_unalias("g")
.EE
.RE
.SH "17. AI PRIMITIVES"
.SS "17.1  ai / prompt / stream_prompt"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $r = ai "summarize this", $document
my $r = prompt "What is 2+2?", model => "claude-sonnet-4-6"
stream_prompt "explain quantum entanglement", { _ }  # streams chunks
.EE
.RE
.SS "17.2  tool fn (declarative tool)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
tool fn weather($city: string) "Get the current weather" {
    fetch "https://api.weather.com/" . uri_encode($city)
}
ai "what's the weather in Tokyo?"        # auto-routes to agent loop
.EE
.RE
.SS "17.3  AI collection builtins"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my @keep = ai_filter "is positive sentiment", @comments
my @cats = ai_map    "categorize",            @items
my @class = ai_classify ["bug","feature","question"], @issues
my @sorted = ai_sort "rank by relevance to $query", @docs
my $hit   = ai_match  "find the user-mentioning $name", @rows
.EE
.RE
.SS "17.4  Embeddings + vector search"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my @vecs = embed_batch \@texts             # auto-batched
my $hit  = vec_search $query_vec, \@vecs   # SQLite-vec backed
my @top  = vec_topk 5, $query_vec, \@vecs
.EE
.RE
.SS "17.5  MCP (Model Context Protocol)"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $mcp = mcp_connect "stdio:./my-mcp-server"
mcp_server "myserver", tools => [\\&weather, \\&search]
mcp_server_start "myserver"
# `s build --mcp-server NAME` builds a self-contained MCP server binary.
.EE
.RE
.SH "18. WEB FRAMEWORK"
.PP
Rails-shaped scaffold;
.IR .stk
source files; framework runtime is
.B web_*
builtins. The whole framework + your app + SQLite ships as a single
.B cargo build --release
binary via
.BR "s_web build" .
.SS "18.1  Generator"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
s_web new myapp \\
    --app everything --theme cyberpunk \\
    --auth --admin --docker --ci --pwa --migrate
.EE
.RE
.SS "18.2  Routing"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
web_route "GET",  "/users",       \\&list_users
web_route "POST", "/users",       \\&create_user
web_route "GET",  "/users/:id",   \\&show_user
web_serve port => 8080
.EE
.RE
.SS "18.3  ORM"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
web_create_table "users", {
    id      => "INTEGER PRIMARY KEY",
    name    => "TEXT NOT NULL",
    email   => "TEXT UNIQUE",
}
my @users = User->all
my $u    = User->find(42)
$u->{name} = "Alice"
$u->save
.EE
.RE
.SS "18.4  Templates"
.PP
ERB-style
.B <%= expr %>
,
.B <% code %>
,
.B <%- code -%>
(trim whitespace), layouts, partials.
.SH "19. PACKAGE MANAGER"
.PP
Cargo-shaped manifest. Reproducible builds via
.B stryke.lock
+ content-addressed
.BR ~/.stryke/store/ .
.SS "19.1  Manifest"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
# stryke.toml
[package]
name = "myproj"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2026"

[dependencies]
stryke-utils = "1.2"
stryke-http  = { version = "0.5", features = ["tls"] }
local-shared = { path = "../shared" }
.EE
.RE
.SS "19.2  Commands"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
s install            # resolve + populate store
s add httprs        # add dep
s remove httprs     # remove dep
s tree              # print resolved graph
s info httprs       # store path + version
s update            # bump pinned versions
s outdated          # diff against latest
s audit             # security scan
s vendor            # copy deps into ./vendor
.EE
.RE
.SH "20. CLUSTER & DISTRIBUTED"
.PP
Built-in distributed compute: spawn workers across many machines,
fan-out work, collect results. Single-binary deployment via
.BR "s build" .
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
my $cluster = cluster(["host1", "host2", "host3"])
my @results = $cluster->pmap_on(sub { sha256(slurp _) }, \@files)
.EE
.RE
.PP
The controller spawns
.B s --remote-worker
on each host via SSH. Wire protocol is custom (
.B remote_wire
), bincode-serialized, length-prefixed. mTLS in roadmap; current
plaintext OK for trusted networks.
