.SH "25. EXAMPLES"
.SS "Inline one-liners"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
# Sum stdin numbers:
seq 1 100 | s -ne '$s += $_; END { p $s }'

# Parallel SHA-256:
s 'glob("**/*.txt") |> pmap { sha256 _ } |> e p'

# Filter JSON from URL:
s 'curl_get("https://api.example.com") |> from_json
   |> grep { _->{active} } |> map { _->{name} } |> e p'

# Parallel grep with progress:
s 'glob("logs/*.log")
   |> pmap { grep /ERROR/, read_lines _ } |> e p, progress => 1'

# Sed-like in-place rewrite, parallel across files:
s -i.bak -pe 's/foo/bar/g' *.txt

# Top 10 longest lines from STDIN:
s -ne 'BEGIN { my @h }
       push @h, [length, $_]; @h = sort { $b->[0] <=> $a->[0] } @h;
       @h = @h[0..9] if @h > 10
       END { p "$_->[0]\\t$_->[1]" for @h }'

# Count distinct values via HyperLogLog from CSV:
s 'my $h = hll(14);
   from_csv(slurp "data.csv") |> e { hll_add($h, $_->{user_id}) };
   p hll_count($h)'

# Build a static binary for distribution:
s build mytool.stk -o ./mytool

# Spin up a web app:
s_web new myapp --auth --admin && cd myapp && s_web build

# Connect to an MCP server:
my $mcp = mcp_connect "stdio:./my-mcp-server"
ai "summarize the data", mcp => $mcp
.EE
.RE
.SS "REPL one-liners"
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
stryke❯ ls
stryke❯ pwd
stryke❯ pushd /tmp
stryke❯ curl_get "https://example.com" |> length
stryke❯ tree(".", 2) |> p
stryke❯ help pmap                   # opens hover-doc TUI
stryke❯ man ls                      # spawns system man(1)
stryke❯ keys %b |> grep { /^cms/ }   # introspect builtins by prefix
stryke❯ history(-5)                  # 5th-from-last input
stryke❯ exit
.EE
.RE
.SH "26. PERFORMANCE"
.PP
.B Hot-path JIT.
Cranelift block-JIT compiles hot loops to native code; deoptimization
back to bytecode VM is a frame-pointer swap. Disable with
.BR --no-jit .
.PP
.B Per-run profiling.
.B --record
or
.B STRYKE_RECORD=1
records every run to
.IR ~/.stryke/perf.sqlite .
View via
.BR perfview :
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
s perfview                          # top 20 slowest
s perfview top 5                    # top 5
s perfview name rosetta             # path substring filter
s perfview since 24h                # last 24 hours
s perfview slowest                  # sort by duration desc (default)
s perfview fastest                  # sort asc
s perfview path /abs/script.stk     # exact-path filter
.EE
.RE
.PP
.B Flamegraph.
.B --flame
prints terminal bar charts (TTY) or SVG (when piped to a file):
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
s --flame myscript.stk > flame.svg
.EE
.RE
.PP
.B Bytecode disassembly.
.B --disasm
prints the compiled program before running.
.PP
.B Release-build tuning.
The release profile uses
.B "lto = \"fat\""
,
.B "codegen-units = 1"
,
.B "panic = \"abort\""
,
.B "strip = true"
to maximize per-builtin density. 44 MB binary for 10,459 primaries
≈ 4.3 KB amortized per builtin.
.SH "27. DEBUGGING"
.PP
.TP
.B --ast
Dump parsed AST as JSON.
.TP
.B --disasm
Print bytecode before running.
.TP
.B --explain \fICODE\fR
Print the expanded hint for an error code (e.g.
.BR E0001 ).
.TP
.B -d
Run under debugger.
.TP
.B -D\fIFLAGS\fR
Set debug flags (Perl-compat letters).
.TP
.B --profile
Wall-clock profile (VM op lines).
.TP
.B --flame
Flamegraph.
.SH "28. PERL 5 COMPATIBILITY"
.PP
Stryke runs unmodified Perl 5 scripts in
.B --compat
mode (no stryke extensions enabled). The compatibility surface
covers:
.IP \(bu 2
All Perl 5 core builtins (
.IR perlfunc (1)).
.IP \(bu 2
Regex (
.B m// s/// tr/// qr//
) with full Perl 5.40 syntax.
.IP \(bu 2
References, complex data structures.
.IP \(bu 2
Bless / OOP via
.BR bless .
.IP \(bu 2
.BR BEGIN ", " END ", " INIT ", " CHECK ", " UNITCHECK ", " DESTROY ", " AUTOLOAD .
.IP \(bu 2
.B Carp::
,
.B Scalar::Util::
,
.B List::Util::
,
.B POSIX::
shipped in
.BR %INC .
.PP
Parity vs Perl is enforced by 20,056
.B parity/cases
test cases that run both interpreters on every CI cycle and assert
byte-identical output.
.PP
Differences from Perl 5:
.IP \(bu 2
Stryke
.B len
is codepoint-counting; Perl
.B length
is byte-counting. Stryke
.B []
slices are codepoint-indexed; Perl is byte-indexed. Pick one
coordinate system per expression.
.IP \(bu 2
Stryke
.B sub
and
.B fn
are interchangeable; idiomatic stryke uses
.BR fn .
.IP \(bu 2
Stryke has its own
.B $_0
/
.B $_1
positional block params (replaces Perl's magic
.B $a
/
.BR $b ).
.SH "29. EXIT STATUS"
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Script error / non-zero exit from program / die uncaught.
.TP
.B 2
CLI argument parse error.
.TP
.B 130
Interrupted by SIGINT.
.TP
.B 137
Killed by SIGKILL.
.TP
.B 139
Segfault.
.SH "30. SIGNALS"
.PP
Signal handlers register via
.BR %SIG :
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
$SIG{INT} = sub { p "caught Ctrl-C"; exit 0 };
$SIG{TERM} = "IGNORE";
$SIG{__DIE__} = sub { ... };
.EE
.RE
